var e=`Golden Staircase`,t=`en-GoldenStaircase`,n=[{title:``,paragraphs:[{class:`b34`,text:`\r`},{class:`b35`,text:` All glory to Ňörńę Guru and Ňörńę GaurńĀŠĻÖga`},{class:`b36`,text:` Golden Staircase`},{class:`b87`,text:` Practical steps on <br />the path of devotional service-life fulfilment`},{class:`b37`,text:` Compiled from informal discourses given between<br />1981 and 1985 by`},{class:`b66`,text:` Ňörńęla Bhakti RakŠĻ£ak Ňörńędhar Dev-GoswńĀmńę MahńĀrńĀj`},{class:`b42`,text:` Founder-ńÄchńĀrya of Ňörńę Chaitanya SńĀraswat MaŠĻ≠h, <br />Nabadwńęp, India`},{class:`b37`,text:` Published under the auspices of the President-ńÄchńĀrya`},{class:`b73`,text:` Ňörńęla Bhakti Sundar Govinda Dev-GoswńĀmńę MahńĀrńĀj`},{class:`b37`,text:` Transcribed and Presented by`},{class:`b73`,text:` ŇörńępńĀd B.S. TridaŠĻáŠłćńę MahńĀrńĀj`},{class:`b38`,text:` Sri Chaitanya Saraswat Math`},{class:`b76`,text:` ¬© Copyright 1994 Sri Chaitanya Saraswat Math`},{class:`b39`,text:` All rights reserved by`},{class:`b40`,text:` The Sevaite-President-Acharya<br />Sri Chaitanya Saraswat Math, Nabadwip<br />www.scsmath.com`},{class:`b39`,text:` Published by`},{class:`b40`,text:` Ananta Printing & Publishing<br />2827 S. Rodeo Gulch Rd. #3, Soquel, CA 95073, U.S.A.`},{class:`b39`,text:` Published for:`},{class:`b41`,text:` Sri Chaitanya Saraswat Sanga<br />60 Glengarriff Parade, Phibsborough, Dublin 7, Eire`},{class:`b55`,text:` The editors would like to express their sincere appreciation and gratitude to the following devotees for their help with production of this publication and with the necessary funds: J√ĪńĀnńĀnanda Prabhu, Vinod BihńĀrńę Prabhu, Ňörńę ŠĻöŠĻ£abhadev Prabhu, Ňörńę AlwarnńĀth VanachńĀrńę, Ňörńę Narahari DńĀs, Ňörńę VidyńĀnanda Prabhu, Ňörńę ChidńĀnanda Prabhu, Ňörńę MathurńĀnńĀth Prabhu, Ňörńę Adhńęrendra Prabhu, Ňörńę Braja BihńĀrńę Prabhu, Ňörńę Bhakta Bandhu Prabhu, Ňörńę JagadńĀnanda Prabhu, Ňörńęmatńę Devamayńę Devńę DńĀsi, Ňörńęmatńę DikŠĻ£ńĀvatńę Devńę DńĀsńę, Ňörńęmatńę Ňörńę LekhńĀ Devńę DńĀsńę, Ňörńęmatńę Tilak Devńę DńĀsńę. We would also like to give special thanks to ŇörńępńĀd B.A. SńĀgar MahńĀrńĀj for his invaluable help with the final revision and editing of <span class="e3">The Golden Staircase</span>.`}]},{title:`Contents`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` Contents`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Foreword</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Chapter One</span>`},{class:`b57`,text:` <span class="e1">The Conscious Sky</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Chapter Two</span>`},{class:`b57`,text:` <span class="e1">The Eye to See Ňörńę Guru</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Chapter Three</span>`},{class:`b57`,text:` <span class="e1">Seeing with the Eye of the Soul</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Chapter Four</span>`},{class:`b74`,text:` <span class="e1">Test, Taste, and Triumph</span>`}]},{title:`Foreword`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` Foreword`},{class:`b43`,text:` I feel very fortunate to have the opportunity to present these gems from the treasure house of devotional service to the Supreme Godhead which emanated from the divine lotus mouth of Om ViŠĻ£ŠĻáupńĀd ParamahaŠĻĀsa Ňörńęla B.R. Ňörńędhar Dev-GoswńĀmńę MahńĀrńĀj between 1981 and 1985. Known affectionately to his disciples simply as Ňörńęla Guru MahńĀrńĀj, His Divine Grace personified the life of eternality, supramundane knowledge, and divine happiness, and he planted the nectar-seeds of KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa-prema‚ÄĒthe supreme goal of life‚ÄĒin the hearts of the fortunate souls. He extinguished the burning fire of separation we felt in our hearts following the disappearance from this world of the great ambassador of KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa consciousness to the West, His Divine Grace Ňörńęla A.C. BhaktivedńĀnta SwńĀmńę PrabhupńĀd, simultaneously fulfilling our cherished desires for spiritual nourishment and inspiring within us an ever greater thirst for spiritual perfection.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The topics presented here have been selected to illustrate the proper and practical way for a sincere sńĀdhaka (aspirant) to progress on the path of pure devotional service to the Supreme Lord Ňörńę KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa, especially in His form as Ňörńę Chaitanya MahńĀprabhu. Ňörńęla Guru MahńĀrńĀj repeatedly emphasised that the path should be followed carefully, step by step, without omitting anything, lest one fall into the traps of either sahajiyńĀism (imitationism) or mńĀyńĀvńĀd (impersonalism). He taught that by always keeping sńĀdhu-saŠĻÖga (association of good devotees)‚ÄĒeither personally or through their ŇõikŠĻ£ńĀ (instructions), by chanting the Holy Names of the Lord with sincerity and faith, and by rendering loving service to Ňörńę Guru and the VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáavas, one could steadily progress on the path back to Godhead.`},{class:`b44`,text:` This progress continues and accelerates by our acceptance of ever higher conceptions and elimination of lower ones, and such progress is infinite, going beyond the taŠĻ≠astha region of VirajńĀ (nirvńĀŠĻáa), the goal of the Buddhists, the brahma-jyoti, the goal of the yogńęs, and onward through Ňöivaloka to the spiritual abodes of VaikuŠĻáŠĻ≠ha, AyodhyńĀ, DvńĀrakńĀ, MathurńĀ, and finally Goloka VŠĻõndńĀvan. There, the Supreme is worshipped as Ňörńę Ňörńę RńĀdhńĀ-Govinda in Vraja DhńĀm or as Their combined form as Ňörńę Chaitanya MahńĀprabhu in Nabadwńęp DhńĀm, and it is by Their own grace that one may ultimately attain the inconceivably high position of service to the servants of the servants of Ňörńęmatńę RńĀdhńĀrńĀŠĻái Herself, which is the ultimate goal of the GauŠłćńęya VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáavas.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Preliminary instructions regarding the process for controlling the mind and senses and the principles of devotional behaviour have been given in books such as <span class="e3">Ňörńę UpadeŇõńĀmŠĻõta</span> by Ňörńęla RŇępa GoswńĀmńę, and carefully following this advice in a properly-adjusted way will ensure genuine progress on the path of bhakti. Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj spoke at length on all these topics, but he always emphasised that it is one‚Äôs sincere internal hankering for the Lord‚Äôs service and the genuine feeling of one‚Äôs own incapacity which are the real keys to realising ŇõaraŠĻáńĀgati, the pure soul‚Äôs surrender.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Ultimately, when genuine divine love awakens within the soul, that love will itself direct the soul to his or her best serving location within a particular serving group (<span class="e3">svarŇępeŠĻáa vyavasthitiŠł•</span>) imbued with one of the predominant serving mellows of either servitorship (dńĀsya), friendship (sakhya), guardianship (vńĀtsalya), or the all-inclusive mellow of amorous love (madhura-rasa). Ňörńęla Guru MahńĀrńĀj explained that within these rasas there are divisions and subdivisions, heads of groups and their followers, right-wing and left-wing parties‚ÄĒso much gradation, all of which is ultimately arranged by the Supreme Lord‚Äôs own yogamńĀyńĀ potency to provide a dynamic interplay of ‚Äėvariety-in-oneness‚Äô by which the Lord‚Äôs Pastimes (lńęlńĀ) are supported, nurtured, and enhanced.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The Infinite is not static (nirviŇõeŠĻ£) but dynamic, and that dynamism generates sweetness in service through both union and separation. Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj‚Äôs explanations of these finer points and his revelations of the inner meaning of the Ňõlokas of <span class="e3">Ňörńęmad Bhagavad-gńętńĀ</span> and <span class="e3">Ňörńęmad BhńĀgavatam</span> and the gńĀyatrńę and other mantras give such new dimensions of depth to one‚Äôs consciousness and nourishment to one‚Äôs devotional creeper (bhakti-latńĀ) that they are impossible for the truly fortunate souls to ignore.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The devotees who were introduced to the teachings of pure devotional theism by the unparalleled preceptor and ŇõaktyńĀveŇõ-avatńĀr Ňörńęla A.C. BhaktivedńĀnta SwńĀmńę PrabhupńĀd will find in this book a very sweet and glorious illumination of his teachings. The ‚Äėmatchless gift‚Äô of KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa consciousness which Ňörńęla PrabhupńĀd gave to the West must be carefully accepted in the heart and preserved and nurtured there. That is only possible by the supporting strength of the devotional illumination given by great beacon lights of the spiritual world such as Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj, whom Ňörńęla PrabhupńĀd loved and revered as his own ŇöikŠĻ£ńĀ-guru in spiritual matters. The fortunate and awakened soul must see the value of this spiritual interchange as a cause of growth if he is to really progress towards the all-harmonising Truth beyond all material sectarian concerns.`},{class:`b44`,text:` It is also my heartfelt feeling that the legacy of both Ňörńęla PrabhupńĀd and Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj is being carefully preserved, practised, and preached by Ňörńęla Guru MahńĀrńĀj‚Äôs successor, Ňörńęla Bhakti Sundar Govinda MahńĀrńĀj, and that in the unbearable fire of separation from those two great souls, our hearts may be given hope once again.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The Lord mercifully comes as the ńÄchńĀrya to deliver Himself to the souls of this world. All glories to BhagavńĀn Ňörńę KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa and Ňörńę Chaitanya MahńĀprabhu! I offer my sincere daŠĻáŠłćavat praŠĻáńĀms to all the holy VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáavas through whom we may have the benediction of divine faith‚Äôs revelation.`},{class:`b56`,text:` Humbly,`},{class:`b56`,text:` SwńĀmńę B.S. TridaŠĻáŠłćńę`},{class:`b56`,text:` Disappearance day of Ňörńęla ŇörńęnivńĀs ńÄchńĀrya`},{class:`b45`,text:` 21 November 1993`}]},{title:`The Conscious Sky`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b58`,text:` Chapter One`},{class:`b47`,text:` The Conscious Sky`},{class:`b43`,text:` The original substance is spirit, is soul, is consciousness, and matter forms a part of that conscious portion, that conscious substance. It is not that matter has produced consciousness, but it is in one part of consciousness. Consciousness is infinite, and everything is in that ocean. Somewhere there is ice, somewhere moss, somewhere iron‚ÄĒthey are all in that ocean, these different conceptions. But consciousness is all-in-all, and everything has its shelter there. Just as you find patches of clouds in the sky or so many specks of dust in the air, so the material conception is there in the sky of consciousness. It is a sky‚ÄĒthe conscious sky‚ÄĒand somewhere there are patches of clouds or dust. You can‚Äôt see the air, but the dust is in the air! You can‚Äôt see the sky‚ÄĒthe actual ether‚ÄĒbut the clouds are in the sky! So, the background is consciousness, and therein we find somewhere is dust, somewhere is a cloud.`},{class:`b69`,text:` Darwin and others have proposed that consciousness was originally generated from material elements, but my response to that is, ‚ÄúFossil fatherism? Crush it and establish a spiritual infinite!‚ÄĚ It is all spiritual. The ‚Äėfossil conception‚Äô is a part of so many conceptions in the spiritual plane. Consciousness is in the background, and there are developed positions, gradations, within consciousness‚ÄĒBhŇę, Bhuva, Sva, Maha, Jana, Tapa, Satya, Brahmaloka‚ÄĒand when service is added, it is enhanced. A sweet structure begins from the point when service is added to consciousness. Service can construct a beautiful capital, a beautiful country. It is there, and you have only to feel it, enter, and take up your appointed service. You will think, ‚ÄúThis is my home! This appointment feels very friendly to me. Now I have come home.‚ÄĚ This is the innate capacity or substance, innate nature‚ÄĒsvarŇęp‚ÄĒwhich is presently covered by ignorance, by misconception.`},{class:`b70`,text:` Madness and malengagement`},{class:`b71`,text:` A madman, leaving his own sweet home, wanders in the street and thinks that it is imperative for him to collect pieces of paper or cloth, as if that were his ‚Äėbusiness‚Äô. It is absurd. His brain is focussed in such a direction that he thinks, ‚ÄúIt is my duty to collect these pieces of paper and pebbles.‚ÄĚ In this way he is going on, but what is the real, innate wealth of his heart? If he could only remember his home: his father, mother, other family members‚ÄĒhis sweet, sweet home. But due to his madness, his consciousness is forcibly focussed on some malengagement. Similarly, the position of so many persons‚ÄĒincluding philosophers, scientists, political leaders, and many more‚ÄĒis that their consciousness is focussed toward the external direction, and there they are all busy ‚Äėcollecting‚Äô. Some are collecting more pebbles, some more pieces of cloth or pieces of paper, but in this way they are going on. SwńĀmńę MahńĀrńĀj (Ňörńęla A.C. BhaktivedńĀnta SwńĀmńę PrabhupńĀd) said that, ‚ÄúThe United Nations, UNESCO‚ÄĒall such world committees and barking dogs are both equal. Actually, they are more dangerous because they are capturing the more intellectually-minded people, but they are of the same value. They are casting their own attention toward the material substance based on illusion and misconception, and posing in a very grand way, they are giving so much importance to that thing just as many dogs also bark to have possession of a particular thing. It is not more than that.‚ÄĚ With great courage, SwńĀmńę MahńĀrńĀj boldly refuted them, and this sort of conception is leading us to our higher prospect.`},{class:`b70`,text:` Seeing beyond the perception of the senses`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> Now the weather is starting to become hot!`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> We should not pay much attention to that. It will come and go, come and go.`},{class:`b59`,text:` mńĀtrńĀ-sparŇõńĀs tu kaunteya ŇõńętoŠĻ£ŠĻáa-sukha-duŠł•kha-dńĀŠł•<br />ńĀgamńĀpńĀyino ‚ÄônityńĀs tńĀŠĻĀs titikŠĻ£asva bhńĀrata`},{class:`b54`,text:` (Ňörńęmad Bhagavad-gńętńĀ: 2.14)`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúO son of Kunti, only the engagement of the senses with their objects gives rise to the sensations of cold, heat, pleasure, and pain. But these effects are temporary; they come and go. Therefore, O BhńĀrata, you are to endure them.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` Regarding this verse of the <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gńętńĀ</span>, one scholar, a Mr. Chatterjee, has explained this Sanskrit word <span class="e3">mńĀtrńĀ</span> to mean ‚Äúwhat is measured by our senses, the result of our senses‚Äô measurement.‚ÄĚ In this way, the word <span class="e3">mńĀtrńĀ</span> comes near to the word <span class="e3">matter</span>. It comes to mean matter or the world of material comfort. There are so many different views of the world. An ordinary man‚Äôs estimation of the world and a scientist‚Äôs estimation are different. An astronomer‚Äôs estimation of the world is of another type, the politician‚Äôs view is something else, the socialist‚Äôs, the humanist‚Äôs, the humanitarian‚Äôs views‚ÄĒthey are all different. But if we can come to the plane of the soul‚ÄĒeven the lowest conception of what is the real inner self‚ÄĒthat will help us, and there will be a revolutionary change in our lives. All the things of this world will then seem to be trash, of no value, empty.`},{class:`b69`,text:` Presently, the soul is captivated by a great many things which produce mean consciousness, but the solution is given in <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gńętńĀ</span> how we can achieve control of our senses and gain control over the impulses of our mind. It is recommended there that step by step we try to rise up to the soul‚Äôs plane, eliminating the lower planes: first the field of experience of the senses; then the mental field, the impulse which works through the senses; then the intellect, that which drives the mental tendency; and crossing those, that we try to find that point of light which is the soul. If in any way, by the soul‚Äôs introspection you can perceive the soul, then whatever value you had assigned to this whole material manifestation will turn into ashes. You will see, ‚ÄúMy real identification is here within! It is so wonderful, and valuable, and independent of all the hallucinations I was suffering from by coming in contact with the external world. The inner domain is so high, and my consciousness was focussed so low, on such nasty things.‚ÄĚ That is the highest way to control one‚Äôs senses, one‚Äôs charm for the world, for wealth, women, and popularity.`},{class:`b70`,text:` The astonishing soul`},{class:`b50`,text:` Kanak, kńĀminńę, and pratiŠĻ£ŠĻ≠hńĀ‚ÄĒcollection of energy for sense pleasure, sense pleasure, and popularity seeking‚ÄĒthese three things try to keep us down from consciousness of the self. So, rise up step by step: from the world to the senses to the mind, the receiver of the sense-experience, to the guide of the sense-experience, and finally to the light which makes all these possible. That point of light is near and dear, and the others are like foreign agents who have come to capture me and focus me, that light, towards the rubbish and dung-like things of this world. If after having been focussed here through our senses we become more attentive and see some nasty things, then some realisation will come into our mind causing us to feel that such things are actually foreign to our real self, and only by connecting with them through our senses do we feel disturbed. On the whole, it is like that. Then, upon rising up from the sense-plane, you will find that there is another wonderful land of experience; the ńĀtmńĀ is such a wonderful thing.`},{class:`b59`,text:` ńĀŇõcharyavat paŇõyati kaŇõchid enam<br />ńĀŇõcharyavad vadati tathaiva chńĀnyaŠł•<br />ńĀŇõcharyavach chainam anyaŠł• ŇõŠĻõŠĻáoti<br />ŇõrutvńĀpy enaŠĻĀ veda na chaiva kaŇõchit`},{class:`b54`,text:` (Ňörńęmad Bhagavad-gńętńĀ: 2.29)`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúSome see the soul as astonishing, some describe him as astonishing, and some hear of him as astonishing while others, even after hearing about him, cannot understand him at all.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b69`,text:` Even after giving attention to all these things, still it is very difficult to understand the soul properly. But our inner wealth is so valuable, and our present engagement is so nasty. On the whole, we must honestly admit that our condition is nasty. Our true selves are good, but our present situation is very nasty. But somehow we must get out of the intoxication of these nasty things, because to hanker after and obtain and mix closely with and relish these nasty things is improper for the soul. Whereas upon rising up to the Supersoul area, we find that the greatest fulfilment of our life is in that soil. Whatever we presently consider to be ‚Äėconcrete things‚Äô, to be real, are nasty. We are told to ‚Äėbe realistic‚Äô, but that is to become unrealistic!`},{class:`b70`,text:` Withdraw from knowledge`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e3">Ňörńęmad BhńĀgavatam</span> (1.1.2) says, <span class="e3">vedyaŠĻĀ vńĀstavam atra vastu ŇõivadaŠĻĀ tńĀpa-trayonmŇęlanam</span>: reality is <span class="e3">vńĀstava vastu</span>, the real substance above all of the unreal, imaginary things of this world. All the accumulated knowledge in relation to this world is a wholesale concoction. It is the result of misreading the environment and is full of misinterpretation and misconception. The whole thing‚ÄĒthe vocabulary, the history, the epics, the whole thing¬≠‚ÄĒwhatever has been collected‚ÄĒis all a misrepresentation of the truth, and we are in the midst of that. We are captivated within that, but at the same time we have the capacity to enter the plane of real life because we are a particle of that higher world. So, we must go back to God, back to home. Home is there. What charm can there be for us here where there is death, and then birth again, and where everything is stale and produces dissipation and suffering? Mortality, suffering, and death‚ÄĒand even then it is not finished, but we must continuously come here again and again and follow the same course of life!`},{class:`b44`,text:` So, try to obtain real relief, and help others also to take up their proper life away from this undesirable atmosphere. We must go back to Godhead, where everything is wonderful. What is that Godhead? Our home is there! Our home, sweet, sweet home. We are a child of that soil, and the scriptures urge us: ‚ÄúYou have got this human life, this chance, so always try, by all means‚ÄĒby thinking, by meditation, by talking, by hearing‚ÄĒto cultivate your own true identity, your noble identity, in your homeland where the soul lives. Always, always, always engage yourself in that. Try to avoid this plane of misconception by any means and enter into that land.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b69`,text:` Going back to Godhead means going back to our own soil, our real home. What is night to us now‚ÄĒthat we will make our day! Where there is presently darkness to us, we are to find light there, and what is so apparently plain and expressively clear, that must be neglected. In our earnest calculation, the entire world of exploitation and self-interest should be kicked into the darkness, and we should withdraw wholesale from that ‚Äėknowledge‚Äô. And what is dark to us now, we should try to make light by always giving our attention, thoughtful consideration, and adherence to achieving residence in the higher soil: the land of wonders where everything is wonderful.`},{class:`b70`,text:` Shadow, substance, and sound`},{class:`b50`,text:` The spiritual plane is substantial. And why are things as they are here? This is the reflection of that plane, a perverted reflection. So, that nature is also to be found here, but the substance is there, and this is like a shadow. The shadow is unsubstantial, without real existence. The substance is itself real existence. The difference is great. The UpaniŠĻ£ads say:`},{class:`b60`,text:` yasmin vij√ĪńĀte sarvam evam vij√ĪńĀtam bhavati<br />yasmin prńĀpte sarvam idaŠĻĀ prńĀptaŠĻĀ bhavati`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúBy knowing that (spiritual domain), everything is known; by attaining that, everything is attained.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` We have been told this in a general way, but that does not mean that with this consciousness you will arrive in that plane and everything will then be in your fist. No. More and more you will continue to have an intense hankering to approach, to advance, and the more satisfaction you get, the more earnestness you will have to go forward, to go on. It is not to be finished. Here also in the shadow, we do not find any ‚Äėfinish‚Äô, and this is the reflection, so it is a dynamic affair. Go onward, go onward‚ÄĒmore. But substance and shadow‚ÄĒthat is the difference. That world cannot be eliminated. It is constant, eternal. There the soul is finding real substance, but still he is not satisfied: ‚ÄúI want more.‚ÄĚ That is the nature of real substance, and sound will reveal it.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Here, sound is the most subtle thing, but there it is just the opposite. There, sound is a ‚Äėgross‚Äô thing. That is what reflection means, and it is perverted. So, the right hand in the reflection is the left hand, and in the reflection of a tree, the top of the tree is in the bottom position. So, in the plane of substance, sound is the most concrete thing. The subtlemost plane here‚ÄĒthe nearest, innermost plane, that of sound‚ÄĒcan cross over the many coverings of this world and come in connection with the nature of that existence, where the cover of that world is comprised of sound. So, through sound we can go inside there.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Ňörńę Jńęva GoswńĀmńę says:`},{class:`b53`,text:` prathamaŠĻĀ nńĀmnaŠł• ŇõravaŠĻáam antaŠł•karaŠĻáa-Ňõuddhy-artham apekŠĻ£yam; Ňõuddhe chńĀntaŠł•karaŠĻáe rŇępa-ŇõravaŠĻáena tad udaya-yogyatńĀ bhavati; samyag udite cha rŇępe guŠĻáńĀnńĀŠĻĀ sphuraŠĻáaŠĻĀ sampadyate<br />tatas teŠĻ£u nńĀma-rŇępa-guŠĻáeŠĻ£u tat-parikareŠĻ£u cha samyak sphuriteŠĻ£v eva lńęlńĀnńĀŠĻĀ sphuraŠĻáaŠĻĀ suŠĻ£ŠĻ≠hu bhavatńęty abhipretya sńĀdhana-kramo likhitaŠł•<br />evaŠĻĀ kńęrtana-smaraŠĻáayor j√Īeyam`},{class:`b54`,text:` (Ňörńę Bhakti-sandarbha: 256)`},{class:`b43`,text:` First, listen to the Holy Name and cultivate that sound divine. Then gradually, if we do it properly, we can find that next there is colour and figure‚ÄĒnot drawn from this mundane world, but that sound has got its own figure and colour and will show itself.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Although we are presently far away from our original consciousness, when our mind is purified and we are free from worldly, mundane thinking, then like lightning that Divine Name will reveal itself to us, producing some colour and figure within us, within our conception, and that form will be of another type, not like the colour and figure of this world.`},{class:`b44`,text:` From the relativity of that sound will first come the colour and figure and next the quality. In this way, one will spring from the other. Such sound must have such colour and figure, and such figure automatically must have such quality. It will come forth from within.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Then again, that quality is classified according to different intensities relative to the paraphernalia. From the quality, after the quality will come the association. And it will all come from the other plane and enter within the soul‚Äôs conception. Then, from the Name, Form, Quality, and associates will come their mutual transactions, the interaction between all these things, the waves and vibrations of different types‚ÄĒthat is Pastimes, lńęlńĀ.`},{class:`b55`,text:` And then the soul will find that his purest, finest ego, who he really is, also has a part to play in such a position. He will see his own soul in a particular place, a particular location there. He will see, ‚ÄúIn this exact spot, I am there; my self is there.‚ÄĚ In this way, the infinite wave will come.`}]},{title:`The Eye to See Ňörńę Guru`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b58`,text:` Chapter Two`},{class:`b47`,text:` The Eye to See Ňörńę Guru`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> We are often told regarding the Guru and the ŇõiŠĻ£ya (disciple) that if the ŇõiŠĻ£ya is not successful in becoming a completely pure devotee in this life, then the Guru will return by taking another birth. But does the Guru personally take another birth?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> The relationship must continue. Whether that particular soul who was delegated as the Guru in the previous life will personally come‚ÄĒwhether he will again be sent or not‚ÄĒthere is no guarantee, but in any case the disciple will maintain his awareness of that higher connection. He will recognise it just as it was in former stages, although it may be in a different form. It will not be unknown to him. And he will also perceive that ‚ÄúI am not unknown to my master.‚ÄĚ But the Guru‚Äôs external form may not be similar.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Suppose a disciple takes his next birth in a particular country or a particular sect. The Guru may also appear in a particular country or a particular sect, but that the disciple will again come exactly in the same position as before‚ÄĒthat may not be. And that the Guru will also come as he did previously, in that fixed position‚ÄĒthat also may not be. But they will be able to recognise one another. The Guru will know about the disciple‚Äôs previous life, and the disciple will also think, ‚ÄúHe knows everything about me.‚ÄĚ With such broadness of vision, we are to look at our Guru MahńĀrńĀj. So Guru-tattva means it is <span class="e3">sńĀkŠĻ£ńĀd Dharitvena</span>: not only the person, but the person plus something more. And that arrangement is made by the Lord or His svarŇęp-Ňõakti. But whatever the external circumstance, there will be no disturbance regarding the path for the disciple.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> I don‚Äôt know if this is correct, but I have heard it said that if the disciple is not spiritually successful, then the Guru may not return back to Godhead but may remain in this brahmńĀŠĻáŠłća (universe). He may not return to KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa until the disciple can also go.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> If that is the case, then no Guru can ever return to KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa at any time because the continuation of the disciples will go on, so he will have no final result at any time in his life. But we cannot think that it is so. Sometimes he may be deputed himself, or others also may be deputed in that case. But the inner instruction and inner feeling and paraphernalia will be such that in any case the disciples will have no trouble. The officer may change, but the function will go on smoothly. So, the Guru may return‚ÄĒthe NńĀm-guru, mantra-guru, sannyńĀs-guru‚ÄĒthey are all Gurus, but we must recognise something similar in them, and hence we are given the statement about the ontological aspect of Guru <span class="e3">sńĀkŠĻ£ńĀd Dharitvena samasta</span>: ‚ÄúI Myself appear as the Guru, who is simultaneously and inconceivably one with and different from Myself.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b69`,text:` KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa says <span class="e3">ńÄchńĀryaŠĻĀ MńĀŠĻĀ vijńĀnńęyńĀn</span>: ‚ÄúYou should look there for Me. I am there. I am your Guru. With My different types of Ňõakti, by the jńęvas‚Äô recruitment or by any other way, it is My function to take you up to a different place. In every case, I am there. I am there in My madhura-rasa Ňõakti, sakhya-rasa Ňõakti, vńĀtsalya-rasa Ňõakti, or dńĀsya-rasa Ňõakti, and in a general way also.‚ÄĚ Sometimes, one may be recruited by the RńĀmńĀnuja sampradńĀya and then be converted to join the KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa sampradńĀya, the GauŠłćńęya sampradńĀya. That is also possible. We are to remember the eternal link.`},{class:`b70`,text:` Divine unfoldment`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> So, if someone says that the Guru himself will personally come back, that is a mundane conception, a wrong conception?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> Yes. The main thread is there, but it will not always appear in the same form. Although to the beginners one may say that ‚Äúhe will come back‚ÄĚ, ultimately we find that a disciple may even be transferred into another section and then another section so that he may gradually reach his destination. According to the unfolding of his inner necessity, the departmental change may occur. And he will always perceive his own Guru in newer and newer ways. At first sight, he perceived his Guru to be of one type. Then again with progress, he will see the same Guru in another way, and thereafter another new characteristic will be found in his Gurudev. The disciple will feel, ‚ÄúI could not detect so much in my Guru in the beginning. I saw him in one particular way, but now I find that he is something more, and then he is still more.‚ÄĚ In this way, there is divine unfoldment.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In this world, there is unfoldment, and in the higher domain also there is unfoldment. So ńĀveŇõ, the Guru is something like ŇõaktyńĀveŇõ. There is the ‚Äėchance contingency‚Äô ŇõaktyńĀveŇõ who is deputed according to a particular time, place, or circumstance, and there is also the permanent ŇõaktyńĀveŇõ, but in all cases, according to the necessity of the situation and by the divine dispensation of the Lord, the disciple will be connected, and he won‚Äôt feel any distrust; it is the presence within. He will quench the thirst for the full progress of his heart, there will be divine unfoldment within his heart, and again he will begin a new thirst. And that new thirst will be quenched by whom? His Guru. It will be quenched by his Guru, and he won‚Äôt have any feeling of unscrupulousness or anything else. As his internal thirst is being satisfied, he will feel, ‚ÄúThere is my Gurudev.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` Wherever there is unfoldment‚ÄĒgradual unfoldment and full attention given to that‚ÄĒthen we can understand that from the upper side there is Guru. Gurudev is my guide, and as I progress, guidance of different types will be necessary for me. Always new guidance, and my progress will take me into different places, and there a new type of guidance, a new life, will again come. In this way, dynamic life is going on, and the main thread is there: <span class="e3">raso vai SaŠł•</span>‚ÄĒthe pure rasa, pure ecstasy. And my inner heart will approve, ‚ÄúYes, I want this. This is my fate. This is my fortune.‚ÄĚ Otherwise, if any madhyam-adhikńĀrńę is appointed as Guru and has so many disciples, and if he is to come back again and again, then he could never enter into nitya-lńęlńĀ. But that cannot be so. In any case, whoever is connected with a genuine Guru will be satisfied because the Lord is present there.`},{class:`b51`,text:` So <span class="e3">ńÄchńĀryaŠĻĀ MńĀŠĻĀ vijńĀnńęyńĀn</span> is not in name only; it has a very specific purpose:`},{class:`b59`,text:` ńĀchńĀryaŠĻĀ mńĀŠĻĀ vijńĀnńęyńĀn nńĀvamanyeta karhichit<br />na martya-buddhyńĀsŇęyeta sarva-deva-mayo guruŠł•`},{class:`b54`,text:` (Ňörńęmad BhńĀgavatam: 11.17.27)`},{class:`b43`,text:` KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa says, ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt try to limit the ńÄchńĀrya! You may have come up to a high position, but will you then think that you have surpassed that ńÄchńĀrya through whom you received your initial instruction in spiritual life? No, <span class="e3">nńĀvamanyeta</span>: don‚Äôt think that there is less in him, don‚Äôt consider him to be of lower position. <span class="e3">NńĀvamanyeta</span>: I Myself was there! I was there in your primary teacher, in your ‚Äėcollege-level‚Äô teacher, and I am there in your ‚Äėpost-graduate professor‚Äô also! So, <span class="e3">nńĀvamanyeta</span>: don‚Äôt look at only the outside. I Myself am your guide in different forms. It is I.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b69`,text:` <span class="e3">Sarva-deva-mayo GuruŠł•</span>: the ńÄchńĀrya has got more spacious characteristics than that of the ordinary, general VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáava. KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa says, ‚ÄúFor you, I am there. And <span class="e3">mayńĀnukŇęlena nabhasvateritaŠĻĀ</span>: I am backing so many ńÄchńĀryas. There are so many ńÄchńĀryas, and I am working through them. The ńÄchńĀryas are like helmsmen in so many different boats, and I am the favourable wind helping those boats to make progress. So, don‚Äôt limit the ńÄchńĀrya‚ÄĒtry to see him on the same level as Me.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b70`,text:` Universal mind, absolute backing`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> In his purport to <span class="e3">Ňörńęmad BhńĀgavatam</span> 4.12.33, Ňörńęla BhaktivedńĀnta SwńĀmńę PrabhupńĀd wrote something in connection with the story of Dhruva MahńĀrńĀj. He said that Dhruva MahńĀrńĀj was a very powerful devotee and could take his mother back to Godhead, and then he wrote, ‚ÄúIf one of my disciples becomes as strong as Dhruva MahńĀrńĀj, then he can take me back to Godhead.‚ÄĚ This statement seems very mysterious.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> Dhruva‚Äôs mother was his Guru, his vartma-pradarŇõaka-guru, his first guide, just as ChintńĀmaŠĻái was in the case of BilvamaŠĻÖgal ŠĻ¨hńĀkur. Through ChintńĀmaŠĻái, that KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa-function as ńÄchńĀrya came as vartma-pradarŇõaka, and in a similar way Dhruva was initially inspired by his mother; his first spiritual instruction was from her. Next, he received guidance from NńĀrad, and then by dint of his bhajan he attained the next stage, and then again he went further. But his vartma-pradarŇõaka-guru was his mother, and yet she was to be apparently left behind.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The vartma-pradarŇõaka-guru is the one who first gets the kaniŠĻ£ŠĻ≠ha-adhikńĀrńę bhakta started on the progressive spiritual path. But we have to consider the past lives of Dhruva and his mother. In his past life, Dhruva had made more progress, but then in that life it was arranged by the Lord that his mother would get him started in the proper direction, and thereafter he adopted the path of bhajan. Both of them had previous lives of progress in the proper direction, but sometimes a primary teacher may have a student who is an extraordinary scholar.`},{class:`b51`,text:` In my school days, I remember there was a case we had to read about in history class in connection with the famous statesman Edmund Burke and the taxation laws passed by Parliament at the time of the American Revolutionary War. It happened that his service was so much appreciated that he had the title of ‚Äėlord‚Äô conferred upon him, and to make him a lord, his father and then his grandfather were also awarded the title of ‚Äėlord‚Äô. The title of ‚Äėlord‚Äô comes from up to down, but in that case, it went from down to up! The grandson was first given the recognition of lord, and then the father, and then the grandfather. The grandson received the title first by dint of his capacity. So, it may be that because of previous arrangements, a less qualified person may give a push to a more qualified person in the beginning, and in return the more qualified person may later help him. Thus, the Guru will instruct God-consciousness to different people in different places. From different directions one may receive help.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> And when Ňörńęla Narottam DńĀs ŠĻ¨hńĀkur says <span class="e3">chakŠĻ£u-dńĀna dila yei janme janme prabhu sei</span> (he who has given me the gift of transcendental vision is my lord birth after birth)?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> Whenever there is any difference in the spiritual advice we may receive from different directions, we are to see the common thread. However, the absolute position will warrant a higher consideration than the relative one. Both the absolute and relative considerations must continue, because without that, no progress is possible. Absolute and relative‚ÄĒboth considerations must go side by side. But the absolute has the primary position, and the relative, the temporary, shall be evaluated according to what is suitable to the particular time, place, person, and purpose. So, in this, the longest journey of our lives, and for our greatest interest, we are given the truth, the connection of the Absolute, always, and there is unity.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Even in the case of an ordinary Guru of lower type, the ŇõńĀstra has also maintained that link: <span class="e3">parokŠĻ£a-vńĀda vedo ‚Äôyam</span>. If a certain standard of self-discipline such as no meat or fish-eating, etc. is demanded of those who are very much conditioned by lower propensities, then they won‚Äôt come into the fold, but the policy is that they must come. So, some allowances are given. For a particular type of disciple, there will be a corresponding Guru and a similar ŇõńĀstra, but it is with the hope that they will take up the path of progress. The ŇõńĀstras are so generous in going to the lowest section, and the corresponding Guru will also be there. Similar Guru, similar ŇõńĀstra, and similar sńĀdhu‚ÄĒall are extended to the lowest plane to elevate the conditioned souls by a gradual process.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And the ŇõńĀstra has got in its mind that in this gradual process some provision must be given; otherwise, a great many will give it up. That universal mind is there, and that sort of consciousness is in the minds of the ŠĻõŠĻ£is who have prepared those ŇõńĀstras and in the corresponding Gurus as well. The sńĀdhus and ŇõńĀstras are going to the extremity of the sinful area because otherwise there would be no chance for anyone to rise from that level. But generally the disciples, the sńĀdhakas, will take up spiritual practices from their own plane‚ÄĒtheir own level of realisation or inner evolution. They‚Äôll go up from there, and along the way also they will find the appropriate Guru and ŇõńĀstra.`},{class:`b44`,text:` It is just like this: our sight is within a particular spectrum. We can‚Äôt see very intense light or very meagre light either. The same with sound: we can‚Äôt hear very high frequency sound or very low. So, we are working in the relative position. But we are told to stick to the absolute thread continually in order to properly understand the whole. Therefore, don‚Äôt undermine the ńÄchńĀrya. Although you may be seeing some ordinary characteristics there‚ÄĒeating, sleeping‚ÄĒ don‚Äôt undermine him! Otherwise, you‚Äôll be the loser. Just as in the Ganges water, we are not to take notice of the stones, the wood, the foam. Ganges water can purify everything. What is it that can purify? Its water aspect? No. There is another aspect, and if that is analysed, ultimately we will see the order of the Lord. It is His order that Ganges water will purify. So, the purifying power comes from His will; His will is backing that. We shall try to find the absolute backing everywhere, and if we can‚Äôt sacrifice the relative position, then we‚Äôll have to go to the plane of nirviŇõeŠĻ£ (the undifferentiated aspect of the Absolute in which service is absent).`},{class:`b69`,text:` There is a complete system which comprises KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa and His associates of different types, and we want to have our connection with both Ňöakti (the potency) and ŇöaktimńĀn (the possessor of potency). We can never sacrifice either of Them, especially Ňöakti. For example, when RaghunńĀth DńĀs GoswńĀmńę says, ‚ÄúI do not want KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa if RńĀdhńĀrńĀŠĻáńę is not there; rather, I want RńĀdhńĀrńĀŠĻáńę‚ÄĚ, then who is RńĀdhńĀrńĀŠĻáńę? Who is She? She is the one who is full of KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa to the greatest degree, so DńĀs Goswamńę says, ‚ÄúI want RńĀdhńĀrńĀŠĻáńę.‚ÄĚ KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa is there, and in different relative positions He comes to each particular person as sweet, sweeter, sweetest. In this way, we find such relativity.`},{class:`b70`,text:` Harmonising instructions of the upper house`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> It is said there are five principles for bhakti‚ÄĒassociating with devotees, chanting Hari-nńĀm, hearing <span class="e3">Ňörńęmad BhńĀgavatam</span>, worshipping Tulasńę, and residing in the holy DhńĀm. In regard to residing in the DhńĀm, is that for the general devotees or just especially fortunate or more advanced devotees?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> Generally, it means for madhyam-adhikńĀrńę devotees, those who can discriminate. KaniŠĻ£ŠĻ≠ha-adhikńĀrńęs cannot differentiate between the various positions of different personalities‚ÄĒwho is advanced, who is neutral, or who is envious. But, ‚ÄúReligion means proper adjustment.‚ÄĚ Our Guru MahńĀrńĀj used to say this now and then, and that proper adjustment requires sambandha-j√ĪńĀn, knowing what is what. Then, one‚Äôs service will come accordingly, and one‚Äôs necessity, one‚Äôs destination, will be established from that. SanńĀtan GoswńĀmńę is the ńÄchńĀrya of sambandha-j√ĪńĀn. ‚ÄúWho am I? Where am I? What am I?‚ÄĚ All these questions‚ÄĒ‚ÄúWhy am I troubled? What is the real purpose of my life?‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒare answered when there is proper adjustment with the Absolute and the relative. Nothing can be sacrificed.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And one thing we must always keep in mind is that we can‚Äôt investigate all of the subtle, higher knowledge as a subjective researcher. Rather, according to the degree of our ŇõaraŠĻáńĀgati, our surrender, the Truth will come down to make Himself known to us. We must always remember this; otherwise, some spirit of imitation will be created in us. Knowledge of the higher domain is not under the jurisdiction of the intellect, and to think so is very dangerous. Intellectualism is dangerous. It will cause us to think that we have ‚Äėcaught the Infinite‚Äô. It will be negligence of the infinite characteristic, the infinite aspect, of the Lord. He is AdhokŠĻ£aja, beyond the grasp of academic research.`},{class:`b69`,text:` One time, I asked PrabhupńĀd (Ňörńęla Bhakti SiddhńĀnta Saraswatńę ŠĻ¨hńĀkur), ‚ÄúŇörńęla RŇępa GoswńĀmńę gives his explanation of Lord BalarńĀm‚Äôs RńĀsa-lńęlńĀ in one way, and Ňörńęla SanńĀtan GoswńĀmńę gives his explanation in another way, but both get their instruction from MahńĀprabhu, so why is there this difference?‚ÄĚ My Guru MahńĀrńĀj said, ‚ÄúWhy has KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa been called AdhokŠĻ£aja? AdhokŠĻ£aja cannot be harmonised within our intellect. It is achintya-bhedńĀbheda, inconceivably and simultaneously one and different. Both explanations may be true simultaneously. It is achintya, inconceivable. The ńÄchńĀryas have explained that when Baladev is performing RńĀsa-lńęlńĀ, He is actually conducting RńĀsa for KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa in His heart. Externally, Baladev is seen to be participating in Pastimes with the gopńęs directly, but internally He is making KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa enjoy that RńĀsa. Baladev is not the enjoyer Himself.‚ÄĚ These are the harmonising instructions of the upper house, and in this way we shall harmonise things.`},{class:`b70`,text:` Full satisfaction, absolute realisation`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> MahńĀrńĀj, the different animals, insects, and trees in the DhńĀm‚ÄĒhow shall we view them?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> They are wholesale chinmaya. They are not under bondage but are posing in different ways. There are different types of service, and they have their fullest satisfaction in their own plane of service. They imbibe the most blissful internal feeling thereby and do not want any other. In their relative position, they are fully satisfied there. In other rasas also, sakhya or vńĀtsalya‚ÄĒ<span class="e3">yńĀŐźra yei rasa, sei sarvottama</span>‚ÄĒeach person feels, ‚ÄúWhat I have is the best. I have got the best position, and I do not care to go to any other.‚ÄĚ ŇöńĀnta-rasa is also like that. The trees and creepers, the sands, and so many animals and birds are there, but still there is a qualitative difference between them. Uddhava, the highest devotee in DvńĀrakńĀ, aspires to take birth as a creeper in VŠĻõndńĀvan. So, there are qualitative differences within ŇõńĀnta-rasa. In DvńĀrakńĀ also, there is ŇõńĀnta-rasa, but he who has the highest type of sakhya-rasa in DvńĀrakńĀ aspires after the ŇõńĀnta-rasa service in VŠĻõndńĀvan once he has gotten a little peep into the atmosphere of the type of service rendered there. This shows that even the highest thing in a particular place still has its relative position in the absolute consideration. Though the relative position is satisfied there, the absolute always surpasses it; otherwise, the unity, the connection with the whole, would ultimately be dislocated and disorganised.`},{class:`b44`,text:` So, the absolute consideration is possible from any position. Although all servitors are fully satisfied where they are in their own position, they realise the supremacy of VŠĻõndńĀvan. TaŠĻ≠astha-vichńĀr (impartial consideration) is always there, and between the relative and the absolute, the absolute always takes the upper hand. <span class="e3">Sarva-dharmńĀn parityajya</span>: the absolute or ‚Äėrevolutionary‚Äô consideration is firmly established above the relative or ‚Äėconstitutional‚Äô one when Ňörńę KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa says in <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gńętńĀ</span> (18.66), ‚ÄúJust abandon all dharmas, all considerations of social and religious duties‚ÄĒeven the ones that I Myself have established in the various scriptures and described here in My previous instructions to you‚ÄĒand just surrender wholeheartedly to Me.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b55`,text:` Everywhere, the absolute consideration prevails. In connection with Guru, Narottam DńĀs ŠĻ¨hńĀkur has his Gurudev LokanńĀth, but still he aspires, ‚ÄúWhen will the day come when LokanńĀth will take me by my hand and guide me to Ňörńęla RŇępa GoswńĀmńę? When will he surrender me to Ňörńęla RŇępa GoswńĀmńę and give me some engagement there in that camp?‚ÄĚ In this high type of expression, the absolute consideration is also there underground.`}]},{title:`Seeing with the Eye of the Soul`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b58`,text:` Chapter Three`},{class:`b47`,text:` Seeing with the Eye of the Soul`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> Guru MahńĀrńĀj, I have one question about Tulasńę Devńę. The devotees here at this MaŠĻ≠h say that even if their japa-mńĀlńĀ is not made from real tulasńę, when you chant on their beads at the time of their initiation, you turn those beads into a tulasńę-mńĀlńĀ. So, is it important to have japa-mńĀlńĀ made of tulasńę or not?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> There is a higher spiritual consideration.`},{class:`b60`,text:` yasyńĀtma-buddhiŠł• kuŠĻáape tri-dhńĀtuke<br />sva-dhńęŠł• kalatrńĀdiŠĻ£u bhauma ijyadhńęŠł•`},{class:`b43`,text:` There is <span class="e3">bhauma</span> (mundane), and there is <span class="e3">ijyadhńęŠł•</span> (that which we consider worshipable). What I really want to revere, if I consider that to be of mundane nature, that will be an offence. It is an offence. <span class="e3">Archye ViŠĻ£ŠĻáau ŇõilńĀ-dhńęŠł•</span>: if I think that what I am to worship is simply stone, or <span class="e3">GuruŠĻ£u nara-matiŠł•</span>, if I consider Gurudev to be an ordinary man, or <span class="e3">VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáave jńĀti-buddhiŠł•</span>, if I see a VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáava as a brńĀhmaŠĻá, a ŇõŇędra, etc., or <span class="e3">ViŠĻ£ŠĻáor vńĀ VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáavńĀnńĀŠĻĀ kali-mala-mathane pńĀda-tńęrthe ‚Äômbu-buddhiŠł•</span>, if we think that the water that washes the lotus feet of Lord ViŠĻ£ŠĻáu or the VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáava, charaŠĻáńĀmŠĻõta, is just plain water, or <span class="e3">ViŠĻ£ŠĻáau SarveŇõvareŇõe tad-itara-sama-dhńęŠł•</span>, if we think that the Master of all, the Lord of all, ViŠĻ£ŠĻáu, is merely one of many gods, then, <span class="e3">yasya vńĀ nńĀrakńę saŠł•</span>‚ÄĒwe shall have to go straight to hell. This is stated in the <span class="e3">Padma-purńĀŠĻáa</span>.`},{class:`b69`,text:` And in <span class="e3">Ňörńęmad BhńĀgavatam</span>, we find <span class="e3">yasyńĀtma-buddhiŠł• kuŠĻáape tri-dhńĀtuke</span>: that soul who identifies himself with the body, or thinks that the wife and children are my own, or thinks that our worshipful object is something material, or thinks that it is the material element of water at these pilgrimage sites which is purifying, then <span class="e3">sa eva go-kharaŠł•</span>: he may be considered to be a donkey which can be used to carry the food of the cows! <span class="e3">Khara</span> means the donkey which carries a burden, so <span class="e3">go-khara</span> means that beast of burden which cannot even be utilised for the purposes of the human section, but only for the beasts; a very low, beast-conception. So, we are to remove ourselves from the platform of identifying the spiritual with the material. The spiritual is necessary, not the material, and it is imperative that we understand the real position.`},{class:`b70`,text:` RńĀvaŠĻáa deceived`},{class:`b43`,text:` Once, Ňörńę Chaitanya MahńĀprabhu was the guest of a devotee of the primary class belonging to the RńĀmńĀnuja school who was very much shocked to hear about the abduction of SńętńĀ Devńę by RńĀvaŠĻáa. At that time, the devotee managed to give some food to the Lord, but he himself was observing fasting and was always wailing and lamenting. MahńĀprabhu asked, ‚ÄúWhy are you not taking anything to eat?‚ÄĚ He replied, ‚ÄúI want to die. I heard that my beloved Mother JńĀnakńę, SńętńĀ Devńę, was abducted by a demon! If I have to hear that‚ÄĒif that should even enter my ear, then I want to die; I don‚Äôt want to live any longer.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` Then, MahńĀprabhu consoled him: ‚ÄúNo, no, don‚Äôt think like that. SńętńĀ Devńę is LakŠĻ£mńę Devńę herself. She is chinmaya, consciousness personified, not having a body composed of any material elements. SńętńĀ Devńę‚Äôs body is not made of flesh and blood, so what to speak of forcibly carrying Her away, RńĀvaŠĻáa could not possibly touch Her; he cannot even see Her. SńętńĀ Devńę‚Äôs form is composed of such substance that RńĀvaŠĻáa can neither see nor touch Her! This is the fact. So, don‚Äôt disturb your mind. This is the truth, I say, so you take prasńĀdam.‚ÄĚ Then, that devotee took prasńĀdam.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Later, MahńĀprabhu went further south, and in one place He found that the devotees there were reading the <span class="e3">KŇęrma-purńĀŠĻáa</span>, wherein it is mentioned that when RńĀvaŠĻáa came to steal away SńętńĀ, She took shelter by entering into fire, and the fire-god Agni gave some imitation SńętńĀ to RńĀvaŠĻáa, and RńĀvaŠĻáa took that ‚ÄėmńĀyńĀ SńętńĀ‚Äô away. Then, after killing RńĀvaŠĻáa and attaining victory, before taking SńętńĀ from LaŠĻÖkńĀ, RńĀmachandra said, ‚ÄúTo prove Her chastity, She must enter into blazing fire, and if She can pass through that test, then I shall accept Her. For one whole year She was living with the demon family, and therefore I cannot immediately trust Her chastity.‚ÄĚ Then, so many devotees began to weep, but by the order of RńĀmachandra the fire was prepared, and SńętńĀ Devńę had to enter. When the fire receded, SńętńĀ Devńę came out with a smiling face, and the devotees began to cry out, ‚ÄúJay! SńętńĀ Devńę ki jay!‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b69`,text:` This was written in that <span class="e3">KŇęrma-purńĀŠĻáa</span>, and MahńĀprabhu asked the reader, ‚ÄúPlease give Me that original page and insert a newly-written copy in there. I met a brńĀhmaŠĻá who is extremely troubled, thinking that SńętńĀ Devńę was actually abducted by RńĀvaŠĻáa. I want to show him this old page of this book to convince him that I was not just consoling him, but it is written in the ŇõńĀstra that RńĀvaŠĻáa could not touch the real SńętńĀ Devńę because She is consciousness personified‚ÄĒnot matter, not any flesh or blood or bone or any such things.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b70`,text:` The soul has its own body`},{class:`b43`,text:` If a ghost can show his form or a yogńę can show his form, then is not God able to show His form? He can do so by His will. ‚ÄúLet there be water‚ÄĚ, there was water, and when He said ‚ÄúLet there be light‚ÄĚ, there was light. His will is law. Whatever He wants to do, at once it is done. So will He have to have a permanent flesh and blood body? At His will, He can show anything as He likes, and it is all spiritual with no touch of the contamination of any mundane substance. But the eye in the higher domain of reality is not like the fleshy eye here. Everything is there‚ÄĒthe eye, the ear‚ÄĒbut they are not the same as here. Just as in dreams, our fleshy eyes do not work, these ears do not work, yet within our dream we see, feel, walk, eat, and drink. The mind is only ‚Äėhalf material‚Äô, and if even in the mental plane all these activities are possible, then transcending that also is the pure spiritual world, and there is the spiritual eye, the spiritual ear, the spiritual mind‚ÄĒeverything is spiritual. It is possible.`},{class:`b44`,text:` On the battlefield, when two tanks come to fight, the men within the tanks may think, ‚ÄúThe tanks are moving like two demons pushing one another!‚ÄĚ The tanks are crashing together, but the man is within. Similarly, the soul within this body has its own body, its own plane of living, its own food‚ÄĒeverything of its own in the spiritual realm‚ÄĒand this world is the perverted reflection of that realm. We must purely aspire after a life in that spiritual realm, and purity depends on love, and love means sacrifice: ‚ÄúDie to live.‚ÄĚ We have to die wholesale in regard to our interest in life here, and then another sort of interest will awaken within us, and we shall live there in that place. That is our aspiration, and for that we have left all our ‚Äėconcrete‚Äô things‚ÄĒour house, our property, our friends, our father, mother, children, and other relatives. So many things we have left, and we have gone out in the quest of other things. We have no more charm for mundane possessions; we are seeking something which is supramundane.`},{class:`b69`,text:` ‚ÄėMundane‚Äô means under the jurisdiction of mortality; at every second, it is dying. Everything on which we depend for the maintenance of this body is dying at every second. Everything. So, we want to be out of this dying land, and if it is possible, we want to live in a land where there is no death. That is amŠĻõta‚ÄĒthat which is without death‚ÄĒand that is sweet. It is VaikuŠĻáŠĻ≠ha; it is Goloka. VaikuŠĻáŠĻ≠ha means in the consideration of the infinite perspective‚ÄĒthat conception. <span class="e3">KuŠĻáŠĻ≠ha</span> means limitation, and <span class="e3">VaikuŠĻáŠĻ≠ha</span> means unlimited. To live in VaikuŠĻáŠĻ≠ha means to live in the relativity of the infinite whole.`},{class:`b70`,text:` The purest prayer`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> MahńĀrńĀj, also regarding Tulasńę Devńę‚ÄĒI noticed that at this MaŠĻ≠h, while circumambulating Tulasńę during her ńĀratńę here, the devotees don‚Äôt like to chant the mantra <span class="e3">yńĀni kńĀni cha pńĀpńĀni brahma-hatyńĀdikńĀni cha, tńĀni tńĀni praŠĻáaŇõyanti pradakŠĻ£iŠĻáah pade pade</span> (‚ÄúThose who circumambulate Ňörńęmatńę Tulasńę Devńę step by step destroy whatever sins they have committed, even the killing of a brńĀhmaŠĻá‚ÄĚ). Why is this?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> A devotee of higher order must not have any prayer to ‚Äúabsolve me from sin.‚ÄĚ The first-class devotee will pray, ‚ÄúWhatever I have done wrong, I am ready to suffer for that, to the farthing. But my prayer is only that I may get a drop of the nectar of the favour of KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa.‚ÄĚ That should be the prayer of a real devotee.`},{class:`b60`,text:` paŇõu-pakŠĻ£ńę haye thńĀki‚Äô svarge vńĀ niraye<br />tava bhakti rahu bhakti-vinoda-hŠĻõdaye`},{class:`b43`,text:` According to my karma, I may be a bird, I may be a beast, I may be a worm or an insect, I may be in heaven or in hell‚ÄĒI don‚Äôt care about that. According to my own karma, let me suffer accordingly. But my only prayer is, ‚ÄúLet me not be devoid of the favour of KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa; let me get that. I want His grace. I want devotion for Him, only devotion‚ÄĒthat is all I want. Whether I have to enjoy the result of my good works in heaven, or I have to suffer for the misdeeds of my previous life and go to hell, I don‚Äôt care to get out of that. As a result of my karma, I shall have to suffer or enjoy, but I don‚Äôt care about that. My prayer is not to remove the reactions to my sins, to take away any good merit or bad result, but only that I may obtain pure devotion independent of these two.`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúI do not want release from either happiness or suffering; let it be, according to my previous karma. Rather, what I want from this moment on is that I will never try to waste the favour of KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa by only praying to be able to face any eventuality, and that whatever I shall acquire from now on, however small, even a drop, that must be nectar of the highest order, and the lower delegation can deal with the question of heaven and hell.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b69`,text:` For removing our reactions or delivering us from hell or heaven, many lower agents are required; they can do that. But we shall only pray for KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa‚Äôs favour as a positive attainment and never try to minimise our previous karma: the result of bad activities performed due to misconception. I don‚Äôt care about the ‚Äėpassport‚Äô; I want the ‚Äėvisa‚Äô. If I get the visa, no passport trouble will be able to disturb me. It is something like that. So, to merely do away with mńĀyńĀ, misconception, is nothing. The positive attainment in the domain of KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa is a much higher thing. By passing mńĀyńĀ, we can attain VirajńĀ, Brahmaloka. We can get mukti (liberation), the marginal position. But why should I waste my energy only to acquire a position in the marginal plane? All my attempts must be focussed toward the prayer for a position in Goloka, and that will be a gain of the very highest order. I shall pray only for that, and automatically everything else will be accomplished.`},{class:`b70`,text:` SńĀvitrńę‚Äôs encounter with YamarńĀj`},{class:`b43`,text:` There is a story from the PurńĀŠĻáas which illustrates this principle, the story of SńĀvitrńę and SatyavńĀn. SńĀvitrńę was a chaste lady who had acquired special capabilities through the performance of certain penances, and one day she went to the forest with her husband SatyavńĀn, knowing that this day was the day of his death. She knew that this was the day of her husband‚Äôs death, but he did not. While cutting wood in the forest, SatyavńĀn said, ‚ÄúI have a headache. I need to take a nap.‚ÄĚ SńĀvitrńę was prepared, and SatyavńĀn put his head on her lap and slept. In his sleep, he died of heart failure, and YamarńĀj came to take him. First, YamarńĀj‚Äôs agents came, but finding that SatyavńĀn‚Äôs body was on the lap of his very pure and chaste wife, they could not venture to take him.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Then, YamarńĀj himself came and told SńĀvitrńę, ‚ÄúYou leave him; he‚Äôs dead. Leave his body.‚ÄĚ SńĀvitrńę said, ‚ÄúYes, you may take him.‚ÄĚ YamarńĀj took SatyavńĀn‚Äôs soul, but then he saw that SńĀvitrńę, by dint of her penances, was closely following him in pursuance of her husband. YamarńĀj said, ‚ÄúOh, why are you coming? I am taking him. You must go back.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` SńĀvitrńę replied, ‚ÄúNo, I can‚Äôt. I shall go also.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` YamarńĀj said, ‚ÄúNo, you must not come. Why are you disturbing my duty? This is the arrangement of the creator, Lord BrahmńĀ, and you must obey that.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` SńĀvitrńę replied, ‚ÄúIt is better to die than to live without my husband.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` Then, YamarńĀj said, ‚ÄúAll right, I will give you a boon. Accept that and be satisfied.‚ÄĚ SńĀvitrńę asked that her father-in-law and mother-in-law, who were blind, would regain their sight. YamarńĀj said, ‚ÄúYes, they will regain their sight.‚ÄĚ But SńĀvitrńę continued to follow him, saying, ‚ÄúI am not yet satisfied completely.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúThen take another boon.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúWell, if you are pleased to offer another boon, my father-in-law and mother-in-law have also lost their kingdom, so now please arrange for them to be reinstalled in their own kingdom.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúYes, I say they will get back their kingdom.‚ÄĚ But again SńĀvitrńę began following him.`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúAgain you are coming?‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúYes, I can‚Äôt live without the company of my husband.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúTake another boon.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúYes.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúWhat is that?‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúI want one hundred sons.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúYes, you shall have one hundred sons.‚ÄĚ Still, SńĀvitrńę kept following behind YamarńĀj. ‚ÄúNow why are you coming? I told you that you would have one hundred sons.‚ÄĚ She replied, ‚ÄúIf you are taking my husband, then how can I get any sons?‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` Then, YamarńĀj was perplexed: ‚ÄúYes, that‚Äôs true. What can I do?‚ÄĚ So, he appealed to the higher force. SńĀvitrńę‚Äôs boon was sanctioned, and she got her husband back. YamarńĀj had already committed himself‚ÄĒ‚ÄúYou will get a hundred sons‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒso SńĀvitrńę asserted, ‚ÄúYou have clearly sanctioned that I will get a hundred sons; therefore, you certainly can‚Äôt take my husband!‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` The general idea is that if we get some backing from the higher sphere, that will overrule all mandates imposed by the plane of mortality. If we are given a place in Goloka, we cannot be detained in this mundane world. When Tulasńę Devńę can give us a place there, then why should we waste our prayer to her by asking, ‚ÄúPlease clear away the dirt on which I am standing‚ÄĚ? That is self-deception. So, we shall always pray to the higher servitors for the higher service of the Lord. We won‚Äôt care about where we might be; that problem will automatically be solved. If we get some higher appointment in the divine realm, then automatically we can‚Äôt be detained here. Therefore, a Ňõuddha bhakta, a pure devotee, from the core of his heart will never pray for anything else, for that would be a waste of energy. Only, ‚ÄúPure inclination toward the service of my eternal Lord‚ÄĒthat I want. I know nothing else but that, and I do not want anything else.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` A pure devotee won‚Äôt pray for anything but for the higher service of the Lord of his heart. He can‚Äôt even imagine asking for anything for his or her own interest. In Christianity, such self-sacrifice is also present. And greater than that is self-forgetfulness. The self is there, but the servitor is forgetful of that and is cent-per-cent absorbed in attending to the pleasure of the Lord. No self-interest, wholesale self-forgetfulness‚ÄĒthey are unconscious of their own particular interest because it has become merged in the interest of the Lord, the Absolute Whole.`},{class:`b52`,text:` So, one who is aspiring to become a pure devotee should never desire anything else but to purely serve and give joy to the Lord of his heart. When one is unconscious of everything else‚ÄĒ‚ÄúLet it be, whatever He may like‚ÄĚ‚ÄĒthat is pure devotion for Tulasńę, or whomever we are praying to. If one has got that higher sukŠĻõti, that Ňõuddha-bhakti, the seed of prema-bhakti, then he won‚Äôt be able to think of anything else but KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa‚Äôs pleasure. He‚Äôll think only of the pleasure of his Lord, cent per cent, forgetting his own body, mind‚ÄĒeverything. That is the purest type of prayer.`}]},{title:`Test, Taste, and Triumph`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b58`,text:` Chapter Four`},{class:`b47`,text:` Test, Taste, and Triumph`},{class:`b43`,text:` According to one‚Äôs sukŠĻõti, inner adaptability, and grace from above, the soul within will experience awakenment, emerge with some taste, and according to that taste, he will adjust himself with the environment. According to his internal taste, he‚Äôll find, ‚ÄúThese friends, this type of service, this company‚ÄĒthese seem to be my own! This is tasteful, very, very tasteful.‚ÄĚ According to his taste, he will take some particular type of ‚Äėfood‚Äô. Just as when animals are let loose, they will take food according to their own choice, so the awakened soul will be able to select a proper environment for himself. His inner taste will guide him: ‚ÄúThis is very charming; this is attracting my heart. I feel helpless‚ÄĒI can‚Äôt control myself. So much attraction do I feel for this particular thing.‚ÄĚ In that way, he will be guided. Intuition will direct him. In this world, we find intuition, and in the plane of divine life also there is intuition‚ÄĒthe undiscovered tendency in the self‚ÄĒand that will perform the function of selection, elimination, and new acceptance. As we go on with our sńĀdhana, with the process of realisation, elimination, and new selection will come gradually. Gradually, it will take us up.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Why have all of you from the Western countries come to KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa consciousness? You were students of Christianity, mostly, so why has KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa consciousness attracted your soul, your inner heart? You had some sort of religious conception, but why did you leave that, leaving so many traditional formalities and so many friends within that circle? Why have you left them to bring yourself here, in KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa consciousness? For what have you come, taking such risk? The country, the society, the religious conception‚ÄĒyou have left them all and come forward for KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa consciousness and moreover as active preachers. That tendency will again push you into the selection of different departments of service in KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa consciousness.`},{class:`b69`,text:` Our inner tendency, inner liking or hankering, will guide us. ‚ÄúThis particular sort of service is very pleasing to me; I cannot but associate myself with this sort of service.‚ÄĚ That will be the guide; cooperation with the Chaittya-guru, the Guru inside, the ‚Äėdictator‚Äô within. The Guru is outside and inside. When we cannot catch the dictation of the inner dictator Guru, then we must have some guidance from the MahńĀnta-guru outside and from scripture. We always want guidance along the path, and when we reach a certain stage, from there our ruchi may guide us. Our inner dictating tendency may guide us like intuition, just as birds and beasts are guided by intuition.`},{class:`b70`,text:` Weeds curtailing the bhakti creeper`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> Then, MahńĀrńĀj, in this connection, why is it that there are so many practitioners of KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa consciousness who, for whatever reasons, have given up their previous devotional association?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> From a general perspective, the life of wholesale dedication is not a very easy thing to swallow. So many difficulties are in the way: previous tendencies, and also the possibility of offences in the choice of thought, speech, and behaviour due to our free will. The defect is there; it is not a perfect thing. Our free will is very weak and limited. SńĀdhana means elimination and new acceptance, and within that also so many difficulties and disturbances may come from our past tendencies which do not allow us to progress smoothly. Though I know that what I see is a higher form of service, my previous tendencies won‚Äôt allow me to accept that and to undergo the austerities and challenges that are necessary for that service. There are so many difficulties, like weeds. This is described in <span class="e3">Ňörńę Chaitanya-charitńĀmŠĻõta</span>:`},{class:`b59`,text:` brahmńĀŠĻáŠłća bhramite kona bhńĀgyavńĀn jńęva<br />guru-kŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa-prasńĀde pńĀya bhakti-latńĀ-bńęja<br />kintu yadi latńĀra saŠĻÖge uŠĻ≠he ‚ÄėupaŇõńĀkhńĀ‚Äô<br />bhukti-mukti-vńĀ√ĪchhńĀ, yata asaŠĻÖkhya tńĀra lekhńĀ<br />‚ÄėniŠĻ£iddhńĀchńĀra‚Äô, ‚ÄėkuŠĻ≠ńęnńĀŠĻ≠ńę‚Äô, ‚Äėjńęva-hiŠĻĀsana‚Äô<br />‚ÄėlńĀbha‚Äô, ‚ÄėpŇęjńĀ‚Äô, ‚ÄėpratiŠĻ£ŠĻ≠hńĀdi‚Äô yata upaŇõńĀkhńĀ-gaŠĻáa<br />seka-jala pńĀ√ĪńĀ upaŇõńĀkhńĀ bńĀŠłći‚Äô yńĀya<br />stabdha ha√ĪńĀ mŇęla-ŇõńĀkhńĀ bńĀŠłćite nńĀ pńĀya`},{class:`b54`,text:` (Ňörńę Chaitanya-charitńĀmŠĻõta: Madhya-lńęlńĀ, 19.151, 158-60)`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúAccording to their karma, all living entities are wandering throughout the entire universe. Some are being elevated to the upper planetary systems, and some are going down into the lower planetary systems. Out of many millions of wandering living entities, one who is very fortunate gets the opportunity to associate with a bona fide spiritual master by the grace of KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa. By the mercy of both KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa and the spiritual master, such a person receives the seed of the creeper of devotional service.`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúUnwanted weeds growing with the bhakti creeper are forbidden acts, violence, duplicity, mundane profiteering, adoration and popularity, etc. All these are weeds. If one does not distinguish between the bhakti-latńĀ creeper and the weeds, then the sprinkling of water in the form of devotional practices such as hearing and chanting is misused because the weeds are nourished while the bhakti-latńĀ creeper is curtailed.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` The creeper of devotion becomes a sprout and gradually grows. Ňörńęla KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáadńĀs KavirńĀj GoswńĀmńę says here that along with the main creeper of devotion there are also many weeds, and when the creeper receives watering and nourishing, those weeds also grow up as well. <span class="e3">LńĀbha</span> means gain‚ÄĒthe apparent gain of something, mainly position. But that position and pŇęjńĀ‚ÄĒappreciation‚ÄĒwhich the sńĀdhaka receives may then create so many other enemies within him. From the previous tendencies, new enemies come; maybe the desire to accumulate money for self-interested purposes or the desire to get the love of women, and then there is hankering for pratiŠĻ£ŠĻ≠hńĀ‚ÄĒfame and popularity. So many things may come. When one is ‚Äėgoing up‚Äô, so many difficulties come on the way to check him, but we must consciously shun those things. So many difficulties come on the way, and we must save ourselves from all of the many internal enemies to our aspiration with the help of Guru, sńĀdhu, scripture, and our own sincerity. Then, gradually we shall grow.`},{class:`b69`,text:` And at each new stage that we advance to, there also we shall find some other difficulty. So the path of inner evolution is not strewn with roses; it is a difficult path to walk. As we get nearer to the goal we become more and more free, but in the beginning various difficulties do come to check us. Our previous karma-phala, the ‚Äėfruits‚Äô of our previous actions, will return to be tasted by us, and tendencies of different types will chase us to try to keep us within their jurisdiction. But upon meeting those difficulties and surpassing them‚ÄĒconquering them‚ÄĒwe shall progress higher and higher, and the difficulties will lessen. Still something may remain, especially pratiŠĻ£ŠĻ≠hńĀ.`},{class:`b70`,text:` More humility: less opposition`},{class:`b59`,text:` tŠĻõŠĻáńĀd api sunńęchena taror iva sahiŠĻ£ŠĻáunńĀ<br />amńĀninńĀ mńĀnadena kńęrtanńęyaŠł• sadńĀ hariŠł•`},{class:`b54`,text:` (ŇöikŠĻ£ńĀŠĻ£ŠĻ≠akam: 3)`},{class:`b43`,text:` While treading the path to bhakti, if we are well-equipped with this helpful mood, then we shall certainly meet less opposition. <span class="e3">TŠĻõŠĻáńĀd api sunńęchena</span>: humbler than a blade of grass. I won‚Äôt allow myself to be the cause of any friction with the environment. This will be our first mood and the foremost guideline for our conduct. Second, <span class="e3">taror iva sahiŠĻ£ŠĻáunńĀ</span>: Still, if any attack does come from the environment, then I shall try to bear it silently, without giving any opposition. And third, <span class="e3">amńĀninńĀ mńĀnadena</span>: I won‚Äôt try to gain any popularity, any good name or fame‚ÄĒI won‚Äôt hanker for that‚ÄĒbut at the same time I shall give proper respect to the environment and to everyone who is in the environment. I shall offer respect, but I won‚Äôt desire any respect from others. The more we try to go on our way with this mood and corresponding behaviour, the less difficulty we shall have to face.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Also, those who are in a mission and under the guidance of a higher realised soul can face many dangers. When we go out to preach, we shall have to face many difficulties, but with the help of the higher guidance, we can fight those who are propagating misconception, and we can either subdue them or invite them to meet with the higher leader. In this way, we can give opposition to the forces of mńĀyńĀ and counterattack. At that time, we shall not adopt the policy that we shall give no opposition to the environment. No. When we are engaged in preaching as ‚Äėsoldiers‚Äô, we shall approach and face the opposition, and we shall try to ‚Äėdisarm‚Äô him. And if we can‚Äôt, then we shall invite him to our Guru to be disarmed.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In this way, I shall go on, carrying out the orders of the VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáava. And if in some way I am ‚Äėwounded‚Äô by the local environment in that attempt, then my spiritual stamina will increase as a result of following the order of the higher agent‚ÄĒVaiŠĻ£ŠĻáava-sevńĀ, and I shall be more greatly benefitted thereby.`},{class:`b69`,text:` I want VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáavńę-pratiŠĻ£ŠĻ≠hńĀ. I won‚Äôt want any popularity from the ordinary public‚ÄĒthey are almost insane‚ÄĒbut I want a position in the eye of my master, my Gurudev, that, ‚ÄúYes, he is a promising boy. He will spiritually prosper.‚ÄĚ When my higher guardians look upon me with some affectionate encouragement, that will be my capital. Their goodwill and liking for me will be my capital on my passage toward the higher realm. When we are alone in a solitary place and going on with chanting the Holy Name, then of course this <span class="e3">tŠĻõŠĻáńĀd api sunńęchena</span> must be strictly observed at all times. But when fighting under a ‚Äėgeneral‚Äô in a preaching campaign, then our external demeanour should be a little different, more towards carrying out the order of that higher spiritual general. That will be more gainful.`},{class:`b70`,text:` The meaning of sannyńĀs for the VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáava`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> Since the general order to go out and preach has been very broadly given to all devotees by Lord Chaitanya MahńĀprabhu, what is the special utility of the sannyńĀs order in our sampradńĀya when MahńĀprabhu has said that it is forbidden in this Age of Kali?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> The answer is explained in <span class="e3">Ňörńę Chaitanya-charitńĀmŠĻõta</span>. This is a general question not only for the GauŠłćńęya sampradńĀya, but also for the followers of RńĀmńĀnuja, Madhva ńÄchńĀrya, and even ŇöaŠĻÖkar ńÄchńĀrya. The Buddhists may not care for the directions of the PurńĀŠĻáas, but the ŇöaŠĻÖkar school and the VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáava schools accept sannyńĀs. ŇöaŠĻÖkar was a sannyńĀsńę, and for the most part his successors were all sannyńĀsńęs as well. This is true of RńĀmńĀnuja also, Madhva ńÄchńĀrya, and the ViŠĻ£ŠĻáu SwńĀmńę sampradńĀya also.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The interpretation is this: in Kali-yuga, sannyńĀs in the strict sense of karma-sannyńĀs is forbidden. Karma-sannyńĀs means that you leave everything, and that type of sannyńĀs is not possible in Kali-yuga. It is described in the ŇõńĀstras that in Satya-yuga, as long as a man‚Äôs bones exist, that is how long he will live. Along with the longevity of the bones, the life will be there. In TretńĀ-yuga, life may be maintained by the nervous system, but it is stated that in Kali-yuga, <span class="e3">kalńĀv annagatńĀŠł• prńĀŠĻáńĀŠł•</span>: one‚Äôs longevity depends on food. Therefore, sannyńĀs in the strict sense is not possible in Kali-yuga.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Previously, VńĀlmńęki was engaged in tapasya for so many years that the insects captured his whole body and reduced the flesh into earth, yet he remained present within his bones. Then later, by the help of some spiritual miracle, his whole body was restored. But in Kali-yuga, without food it is not possible to live. All penances have been especially adjusted for Kali-yuga, and the only continuous fast allowed in Kali-yuga is for twenty-four hours, not more than that. In other ages, at least twelve days fasting was generally done. If a person had done anything wrong, then according to the smŠĻõti ŇõńĀstra, twelve days fasting was the standard punishment for any sins. But in Kali-yuga, twenty-four hour fasting is the maximum because without food a man cannot survive.`},{class:`b44`,text:` If he were to take karma-sannyńĀs while being so extremely dependent on material giving and taking, then he wouldn‚Äôt be able to maintain his existence. But the life of VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáava tridaŠĻáŠłća-sannyńĀsńę, which is not very extreme‚ÄĒtake prasńĀdam, do service‚ÄĒis a sort of modified form based on <span class="e3">yuktńĀhńĀra-vihńĀraŇõ cha</span>, and one living according to this principle can take sannyńĀs.`},{class:`b51`,text:` MahńĀprabhu took sannyńĀs, ŇöaŠĻÖkar ńÄchńĀrya, RńĀmńĀnuja‚ÄĒall the pioneers of the different sampradńĀyas took sannyńĀs. That has been interpreted as karma-sannyńĀs, but still, sannyńĀs is of several kinds. There is also vidvat-sannyńĀs, which is considered by the salvationist section to be the highest. Their idea is that when one has fully realised that his connection with this material realm is a negative one, he will finish his material encasement and enter into the spiritual sphere. When he is fully established in this firm consciousness that ‚Äúmy connection with the material world will be injurious to me‚ÄĚ, he will then relinquish his body and go away to the spiritual sky. That is vidvat-sannyńĀs. There is also narottam-sannyńĀs:`},{class:`b59`,text:` yaŠł• svakńĀt parato veha jńĀta-nirveda ńĀtmavńĀn<br />hŠĻõdi kŠĻõtvńĀ hariŠĻĀ gehńĀt pravrajet sa narottamaŠł•`},{class:`b54`,text:` (Ňörńęmad BhńĀgavatam: 1.13.27)`},{class:`b43`,text:` In the narottam system of sannyńĀs, one has realised the presence or existence of God within his heart, and thinking of Him, he leaves his present engagement and duties of the household and remains outside, anywhere and everywhere‚ÄĒunder a tree or in a cave or wherever‚ÄĒcareless of his physical needs. He does not immediately relinquish his body, but he takes whatever food he gets, and when he does not get any food, he fasts, and in this way he goes on. He leaves the household for good. That is narottam-sannyńĀs.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And there are also different stages of sannyńĀs mentioned in the ŇõńĀstra: kuŠĻ≠ńęchaka, bahŇędaka, haŠĻĀsa, and paramahaŠĻĀsa, progressively. But tridaŠĻáŠłća-sannyńĀs is when the sannyńĀsńę engages himself fully in the service of Godhead by spreading His messages and doing some good to the public, and that characteristic is different. It is categorically different. The tridaŠĻáŠłći-sannyńĀsńę is not adopting an attitude or tactic of leaving all of the engagements of this world as a result of becoming disgusted with its many temptations. Rather, he is engaging himself in the higher duty of the upper world through an agent, so his body has got utility. Remaining here, maintaining connection here, he is drawing some higher thing from above and distributing that in the environment. That is another conception of sannyńĀs, and it has positive value.`},{class:`b69`,text:` This is a similar engagement to that performed by the Lord‚Äôs closest associates. When an incarnation of God comes down, His favourite pńĀrŠĻ£adas, His friends and servitors, are also sent by Him to come down to do some service to help Him. There are also sub-agents who have received some engagement from the higher agent, and by moving within this world in that capacity, they can earn more spiritual wealth than those who are very eager to disconnect completely from this material plane. They want to try to utilise their connection with this mundane plane to earn some substantial wealth of the upper house. So, like the Lord‚Äôs pńĀrŠĻ£adas, the tridaŠĻáŠłći-sannyńĀsńęs want to work as God‚Äôs agents.`},{class:`b70`,text:` The glory of the divine feminine nature`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Devotee:</span> MahńĀrńĀj, we know the injunctions forbidding sannyńĀsńęs and brahmachńĀrńęs specifically from mixing with ladies, but what should be the general overall vision of the male section of devotees as we are serving MahńĀprabhu‚Äôs mission together with our godsisters?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">Ňörńęla Ňörńędhar MahńĀrńĀj:</span> According to the varŠĻáńĀŇõram system, generally the ŇõŇędras (labouring class) and ladies are not allowed direct participation in the higher religious functions. Only indirect participation is allowed for them, and they also do not get the sacred thread. Yet a brńĀhmaŠĻá boy can be found touching the feet of his mother! The mother will not touch the Deity of NńĀrńĀyaŠĻá, but her son who is worshipping NńĀrńĀyaŠĻá is touching her feet and taking her feet-dust. Such a position is there in the varŠĻáńĀŇõram system. Women are generally considered unfit or below the standard of engaging in direct service to the Lord, but in the VaiŠĻ£ŠĻáava conception there is no such strictness about that.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In my youth, some sort of disregard grew in my mind about the lady section: ‚ÄúI must keep far away from them. They are untouchable.‚ÄĚ But that notion was amended by my aunt in this way: she noted my nature, my conduct, and once affectionately remarked to me, ‚ÄúOh, don‚Äôt you know that ladies represent LakŠĻ£mńę Devńę? They belong to the same section, and in them the qualities of sacrifice and submission are very clearly visible, so they should be respected. They should be respected, and the aggressive male nature is to be viewed unfavourably. The feminine ego-conception is an ideal of a very noble type wherein sacrifice, the devotional aspect, is very prominent. Ladies are not aggressors; they are sacrifice personified. Whereas the male nature, that is aggressive.‚ÄĚ`},{class:`b44`,text:` Gradually that idea came to me, and I learned to appreciate SńętńĀ, Draupadńę, and so many others, especially the supreme example shown by the gopńęs. The standard established by the gopńęs has shown that self-forgetfulness, self-sacrifice, and self-surrendering reaches its zenith, its highest conception, in the lady-aspect. The passive aspect holds the highest position. That viewpoint came gradually and caused a turnabout within my mind.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Madhura-rasa, consorthood, is the highest position, and within Ňörńęmatńę RńĀdhńĀrńĀŠĻáńę we find the greatest degree of sacrifice and affection. The males are the aggressors; they are responsible for all the difficulties and troubles, not the ladies. That we possess the aggressive nature of a male is the disease in us. Gradually, that perception developed from inside, and ultimately I found that when the female nature is pure and in connection with the supreme lńęlńĀ of vńĀtsalya-rasa and madhura-rasa, it holds the highest position in the topmost realm. And our aspiration is for engagement in the service of Ňörńęmatńę RńĀdhńĀrńĀŠĻáńę.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The position of Ňörńę RńĀdhńĀ is that of the highest service to KŠĻõŠĻ£ŠĻáa, and RńĀdhńĀ-dńĀsyam has been considered by MahńĀprabhu to be the highest attainment. VńĀsudev GhoŠĻ£ says:`},{class:`b93`,text:` yadi gaura nńĀ hata,<span class="e10">	tabe ki ha-ita</span><br /><span class="e11">	kemane dharitńĀm de<br /></span>rńĀdhńĀra mahimńĀ<span class="e10">	prema-rasa-sńęmńĀ</span><br /><span class="e11">	jagate jńĀnńĀta ke?</span>`},{class:`b55`,text:` ‚ÄúWho could disclose this holy, divine fact if Ňörńę GaurńĀŠĻÖga did not personally appear on this earth? Who could let us know, who could inform us, that the highest servitor is RńĀdhńĀrńĀŠĻáńę?‚ÄĚ But GaurńĀŠĻÖga did come, and He clearly showed that the highest conception of service is to be engaged in the service of that highest, negative potency.`}]}],r={title:e,code:t,chapters:n};export{n as chapters,t as code,r as default,e as title};